Comment: The Sicilian has many variations, sharp with tactics and replete with positional strategies. It is important to be at least familiar with this opening, especially if you play 1. e4 One way of tackling the Sicilian is to play a closed variation, 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 or 2. d6  These moves will not allow your opponent to play their "pet" Sicilian lines which they may know better than you. On the other hand the open variations have chances for White as well and can be more fun.

An odd move here, but not necessarily terrible. g3 is often played in the closed lines when f4 can be played but Nf3 is more typically played in open positions. 3. d4 cd4 4. Nd4 would be an open game and allow black to chose his response.

An earlier exchange on c3 with the black bishop would have been silly as this piece is very powerful for black and would give white the bishop pair. Now however Black can exchange the knight which, while a powerful centralized piece, exchanges away one of the few developed white pieces and doubles up White's pawns. White's position is in trouble now.
